04848nam a22008775i 9783110368963DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20152015gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2015008064  a(OCoLC)1050131301  a(OCoLC)952796723  a97831103689637 a10.1515/97831103689632doi  a(DE-B1597)429315  a(OCoLC)919297822  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aBS2675.52b.C69 2015 4aBS2675.52 7aREL0067202bisacsh04a400223  aBC 73002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/9633:1 aCover, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLifting the Veil :b2 Corinthians 3:7-18 in Light of Jewish Homiletic and Commentary Traditions /cMichael Cover. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (345 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die neutestamentliche Wissenschaft ;v21000tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Patterns of Exegesis in Paul’s “Midraschartige Stücke” -- t3. Sequential Exegesis in Hellenistic Commentaries -- t4. Secondary-Level Exegesis in Homilies, Gospels, Treatises, and Greco-Roman Letters -- t5. Digressive Poetics: 2 Cor 3:7–18 as Exegetical Amplification -- t6. Lifting the Veil: 2 Cor 3:7–18 in Light of the Hellenistic Moses-Tabernacle Tradition -- tReferences -- tIndex of Ancient Sources -- tIndex of Modern Authors -- tIndex of Subjects 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat accounts for the seemingly atypical pattern of scriptural exegesis that Paul uses to interpret Exodus 34 in 2 Cor 3:7-18? While previous scholars have approached this question from a variety of angles, in this monograph, Michael Cover grapples particularly with the evidence of contemporaneous Jewish and Greco-Roman commentary traditions. Through comparison with Philo of Alexandria's Allegorical Commentary, the Pseudo-Philonic homilies De Jona and De Sampsone, the Anonymous Theaetetus Commentary, the Dead Sea Scrolls, Seneca's Epistulae morales, and other New Testament texts, Paul's interpretation of Exodus emerges as part of a wider commentary practice that Cover terms "secondary-level exegesis." This study also provides new analysis of the way ancient authors, including Paul, interwove commentary forms and epistolary rhetoric and offers a reconstruction of the context of Paul's conflict with rival apostles in Corinth. At root was the legacy of Moses and of the Pentateuch itself, how the scriptures ought to be read, and how Platonizing theological and anthropological traditions might be interwoven with Paul's messianic gospel.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aGreek literaturexRelation to the New Testament. 4a2 Corinthians. 4a2. Korinther. 4aMidrasch. 4aMidrash. 4aMoses. 4aPhilo von Alexandria. 4aPhilo. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / Paul's Letters.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2015z9783110438727oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831103927390 cprintz978311037431540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311036896340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110368963423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110368963.jpg  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGFb2015  aZDB-23-DGGb2015